MONROEVILLE SCHOOLS CALAMITY DAY PROCEDURE
For the 2020-21 School Year

Starting the week of September 7th Monroeville Schools will announce a Level Red for the district if the following weather conditions exist. Athletic and special event cancellations would be announced by 1pm each day the district is on Level Red.

‚Ä¢ Dangerous Heat Index of 100 or more (EHOVE Bus will transport if EHOVE is in session)
‚Ä¢ Wind Chill of -17 or more
‚Ä¢ Dense Fog
‚Ä¢ Snow/Ice

Students are reminded to take their Chromebooks home each night beginning the week of Sept. 7th.
If there is a need to cancel school before Sept. 7th it will be a district cancellation with no virtual instruction provided by Monroeville teaching staff.

2020-2021 estimated route times are available on the District's Transportation webpage.

Please review our estimated routes with the understanding that these are estimated times. We ask that riders are ready early for the bus during the first few weeks. If you do not see your child's pick-up or drop-off address it is important to contact the Transportation Supervisor, Adam Gerber. EHOVE students who need morning transportation are required to continue meeting at the Bus Garage at 7:30am. Route times are longer than last year due to one less bus route caused by a shortage of Bus Drivers.

We appreciate your patience and please contact Adam Gerber with any questions.

Thank you to Mrs. Meyer, our Director of Student Services, and Miss Poths, our Monroeville High School Building Secretary, for helping create today‚Äôs videos! We also had a group of our high school students help us too! Thank you!!!

The Monroeville School District was just informed by Tim Hollinger, Huron Co. Health Commissioner, that due to the new mask mandate issued by the Governor last week that Face Shields are no longer permitted unless a mask is worn under the shield. This means Monroeville students and staff must wear a mask or a mask with a shield. No shields will be permitted without a mask unless there is a medical or psychological issue that is documented on file indicating that a mask cannot be worn.

7/29/2020 Monroeville School Reopening ZOOM Presentation Questions and Answers

Q: What happens if students or staff test positive for Covid during the school year?
A: Student or Staff member immediately masked if not already wearing a mask,
1. Immediately Quarantined with observation
2. Immediately removed from the building
3. Health Department Immediately notified
4. We will follow the guidance on a case-by-case basis from the Huron County Public Health Department.

Q: What staff members will be requiring masks in their classrooms? How is this determined?
A: At-risk teachers will be able to determine if students are to wear masks in their room

post_text: Lefty Grove is required to cancel this years summer baseball season. Adam Gerber will soon be in contact with everyone that paid a registration fee to organize your refund.
shared_text:
Lefty Grove Baseball League, Norwalk Ohio is feeling sad.
May 1 at 3:41 PM ¬∑

Due to circumstances beyond our control, there will not be a Lefty Grove Baseball League 2020 season. This decision was based on multiple things ‚Äì City of Norwalk Parks & Recreation Departments Summer Youth and Adult Programs as well as other area youth sports have been cancelled. it will be difficult to implement proper safety measures. Our children‚Äôs safety is our priority.

Parents and guardians, please watch your e-mails in the next couple of weeks. We will be offering the options of either a refund, or if your child is still eligible for playing next year, we can hold the money for the next season.
Please do not send messages to us here on FB about your preference ‚Äì only use the e-mail option or give the information to the person who calls you.

Lefty Grove decision to cancel upcoming season does not apply to the Legends travel teams. Contact your Legends coach for details on the upcoming travel baseball season.

We look forward to seeing everyone at the VFW fields in 2021.

post_text: Mrs. Zureich‚Äôs first graders have started their study of plants. Today they learned how insects help plants grow through the transfer of pollination. They used cheese puffs to represent pollen that gets stuck on insects‚Äô bodies, and drank nectar through a straw. When drinking the nectar, the students got the pollen from their hands onto the flower, simulating the transfer of pollen. What an amazing learning experience!!!

post_text:
Citizens of Monroeville

On behalf of the Board of Education and myself I want to sincerely thank the citizens of the Monroeville Local School district for your show of support for our district by passing the Renewal of the Permanent Improvement Levy in this year's election! Without the passage of the PI levy the finances of the district would have been severely impacted. The PI money can only be used for purchases lasting more than 5yrs like busses and equipment. With the PI money the district would have to use General Fund Money to make up the difference.

Our district continues to make great strides in student academic achievement, creating new and exciting opportunities for our students, and in financial stability. None of this would be possible without the ongoing support of our community.

Again, Thank you all for that support!

--
G. Ralph Moore
Superintendent, Monroeville Local Schools

Ohio State Report Cards Released
On Friday, September 14th Ohio school districts will find out how they performed during the 2017-18 school year. What‚Äôs new: An overall letter grade for each school and school district, a feature school officials have long anticipated.
The report cards will also evaluate school districts on several standards ‚Äî achievement, literacy, graduation rates, among others ‚Äî on an A-F scale. It‚Äôs a similar assessment used for last year‚Äôs report cards. Other new features on the report cards this year include grades on how well schools are helping non-native speakers learn English, stopping chronic absenteeism, how students perform on retaking state end of course exams‚Ä¶ More

2. FROM THIS DAY FORWARD IF EXTREME HEAT IS FORECAST FOR A SCHEDULED SCHOOL DAY AN ANNOUNCEMENT WILL BE MADE BEFORE SCHOOL THAT THE DISTRICT WILL DISMISS EARLY FOR THE DAY AT 11:45AM. BUSSES WOULD RUN THEIR NORMAL DROP OFF ROUTES BEGINNING AT 11:45AM.

PARENTS PLEASE PREPARE NOW FOR A DISTRICT EARLY DISMISSAL SHOULD ONE BE NECESSARY IN THE FUTURE. IF YOU HAVE QUESTIONS PLEASE CALL YOUR STUDENT‚ÄôS SCHOOL OFFICE.
